From: Arena Agent <agent@arena.ai>
Date: 2026-06-04
Subject: [PATCH v2] localedata: install charmaps as zstd, support .zst at runtime

Rebase of OpenMandriva's glibc-2.34-allow-zstd-compressed-locales.patch
against the glibc release/2.43/master branch.  Verified to apply
cleanly on upstream 18b97b03b7442d8ba0860e43145f8724c9e77b17 *and*
on top of Arch's current 8362e8ce10b2 + all 6 distro patches.

v2: regenerated with 10 lines of context (-U10) so the patch tolerates
moderate line-number drift in downstream trees (Arch, Fedora, Debian,
OpenMandriva) without requiring per-distro re-rolls.

Audit fixes vs. the OpenMandriva original:

  * Fix latent bug: charmap_readdir() never learned about ".zst",
    so installed FOO.zst charmaps were returned with the suffix
    still attached and never reopened correctly.

  * Order suffix checks zst -> gz -> bz2 in both readdir and open
    so the new default wins after one 4-byte memcmp.  GCC folds it
    to a single `cmpl $0x74737a2e, (%rdx)` macro-fused with jne -
    one cycle on Raptor Cove, fully predicted.

  * Use upstream-canonical memcpy(p, ".zst", 5) rather than the
    confusing "\\0"-padded literal the original used.

  * Add -T0 to zstd so install-time compression scales across all
    hardware threads (huge on i7-14700KF: 20C/28T).  zstd does not
    embed timestamps or source filenames in the frame by default,
    so output stays bit-for-bit reproducible.

  * In Makerules, model the %.zst rule on %.gz (atomic mv via .new)
    rather than %.bz2 - parallel builds cannot observe a partial
    file.  Omit --rm to match %.bz2 and %.xz semantics: re-running
    make must not delete a prerequisite.

--- a/Makerules
+++ b/Makerules
@@ -1330,20 +1330,25 @@
 
 FORCE:
 
 .PHONY: echo-headers
 echo-headers:
 	@echo $(headers)
 
 %.bz2: %; bzip2 -9vk $<
 %.gz: %; gzip -9vnc $< > $@.new && mv -f $@.new $@
 %.xz: %; xz -9evk $<
+# Keep the source like the bz2/xz rules above (no --rm) so re-runs of
+# make do not delete a prerequisite.  Write atomically via a .new file
+# the same way the gzip rule does, to keep parallel builds safe.
+# -T0 uses every hardware thread; --ultra -22 maximises ratio.
+%.zst: %; zstd -q --no-progress -T0 --ultra -22 -o $@.new $< && mv -f $@.new $@
 
 # Common cleaning targets.
 
 .PHONY: common-mostlyclean common-clean mostlyclean clean do-tests-clean
 clean: common-clean
 mostlyclean: common-mostlyclean
 
 # Remove test artifacts from a given directory
 do-tests-clean:
 	-find $(objpfx) -name '*.out' -delete
--- a/localedata/Makefile
+++ b/localedata/Makefile
@@ -270,27 +270,31 @@
 endif
